review: I loved the pace of the plot and I loved the suspense. I had to keep reminding myself that I didn't really know what parts were true yet...none of it,I loved the pace of the plot and I loved the suspense. I had to keep reminding myself that I didn't really know what parts were true yet...none of it, right?However, there was a murkiness surrounding the abuse and unchecked mental illness that was a little problematic for me. If someone is abused, do we forgive them for their abusive behaviors or at least accept them a little easier? When does a victim become something other than a victim if they've never healed from their own abuse? These are tough questions and I don't expect that Ms Jewell should have tried to answer them. I felt like she was using them to try to make me have empathy for a non-empathetic character. My opinion only....more

review: I am not a fan of Bill O'Reilly, but I typically like his history books. I was looking forward to his usual in-depth look at a topic, this time the SaI am not a fan of Bill O'Reilly, but I typically like his history books. I was looking forward to his usual in-depth look at a topic, this time the Salem witches. I was disappointed by more than half of the book.He started with Salem and I learned things I'd not known before. Great start.Then he moved onto the founding Fathers, especially Ben Franklin, and I thought...ok, I can see how this is a tangent because the Puritan beliefs influenced the decisions being made about the new United States. Especially which amendments to the Constitution made it in and whether to have a national religion. Not witches, but fine.The we went to the book and movie The Exorcist. I should have just stopped, but I kept going...disappointed.Finally we got to the political commentary of the author's note and I was out. review: 3.5 rounded down.This was interesting, but not shocking. Maybe we were all shocked more easily in 1989 when this was first published. The man creeped 3.5 rounded down.This was interesting, but not shocking. Maybe we were all shocked more easily in 1989 when this was first published. The man creeped me out. At times he sounded just as sane as you and me. Then at times he could talk about killing people in cold blood in the same voice/character as he talked about why he changed his mind about going to law school when he was younger.The reporters were fascinating. The way they switched gears when it was clear he wasn't going to "confess" anything while he still had appeals pending was genius. They asked him to talk in third person about what a man who was capable of doing things like that thought, felt, and planned. He opened up about many things when he could do so in the third person. His brain worked a different way than other people. And he knew that. And he didn't consider himself a psychopath. And he didn't care what others thought....more

author: Kilmer, Val
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: I love Val Kilmer in many of his movies. I'm only so-so about his memoir. Partly it was the narration. 3 narrators. 2 males who sound almost identicalI love Val Kilmer in many of his movies. I'm only so-so about his memoir. Partly it was the narration. 3 narrators. 2 males who sound almost identical and then a female. I understand, after listening, why each of them was chosen, but it was jarring at times when the narration shifted. Also, there were times with each of them that I thought they put the emphasis on the wrong part of the sentence or phrase. I'd think to myself "I don't think that's how he would have said it." I think it would have been a different experience if it was in his own voice. I understand why that wasn't possible; I'm just saying it would have enhanced the experience for me.Also, I had a hard time distinguishing between confidence and arrogance on his part. There was a lot of name-dropping. I'm very clear on the fact that he was friends with Marlon Brando. And while I'm certain the number of people who can say that is a reasonably small number, I don't need you to say it multiple times to drive the point home. Some of the stories were touching. Some of the stories were funny. Many of the stories had a stronger spiritual component than I expected and I liked that he shared that aspect of himself. Overall, it was just ok....more

What if you changed majors and pursued a different subject?
